Change has been successfully rebased and submitted as 1e68a88de69cb0aa53e74bf8e1b53001e7b74cb8
Makes sense to collate everything under network plugin than keeping it as separate
You shouldn't be deleting the existing plugin. This is going to break the BMC dump backward compatibility.Not finding any good reason for breaking the opensource coding line here.

Jayanth - Can you please elaborate how backwards compatibility gets broken by collating plugins that are serving the common purpose?  Also, please explain what do you exactly mean by "breaking the opensource coding" ?
Please address the comment on deprecating "ip link"

This is going to be issues with BMC users using infrastructure on top of existing BMC dump content based analysis going to fail. As a good practice we should avoid these situation in  open source coding.  Incase there is strong reason to remove this either usee Dump version based approach or  communicate to community before deprecating the exiting functionality.

The change being proposed here is to fix the issues(data duplication)/improve the quality of the code in upstream. In the current BMC dump framework, every new plugin is going to increase the processing time due to the parsing of plugin config headers. It doesn't also make sense to define multiple plugin files which collects data of a similar type. 

Can you please add specific reviewers who might have impacts/concerns on what is being done here? We can also discuss this in discord if you think this small improvement requires a much wider discussion.
BMC dump plugin design is to supported multiple types of dumps.  Can you provide the performance impact with this plugin approch?

The impact/overhead I'm pointing out is 3 plugins which are ideally required for ALL kinds of dumps being processed independently 

File:iplink
#!/bin/bash
#
# config: 2 30
# @brief: Collect ip link information.

File:ipaddr
#!/bin/bash
#
# config: 2 30
# @brief: Collect ip addr information.

File:network
#!/usr/bin/env bash
#
# config: 1234 30
# @brief: Collect network information

Network folks have already commented in one of the commits that they require all these data to be collected for all kinds of dumps. It doesn't make sense to have three plugin files and running the parsing logic for each, instead of clubbing them together. I also pointed out a duplication of data where and we should get rid of the iplink plugin file itself - this is addressed in Devender's latest patch

I have raised same concerns in the previous review, Network team requested  to add this additional info. See https://gerrit.openbmc-project.xyz/c/openbmc/phosphor-debug-collector/+/52299/2..7//COMMIT_MSG#b7 for details.Better to remove the duplicate data from the new network plugin. existing ip add/link can enable for required dfump types. This will help to support backward compatibility.
We require all the network data in all kinds of dumps. I hope I have clarified why we're trying to merge the related plugins into a same file. Please be specific on the outstanding concerns.

Summary: We should keep the existing plugin to support backward compatibility. Incase Network functional owner believes, need to keep common place for all plugin am fine , approved  https://gerrit.openbmc-project.xyz/c/openbmc/phosphor-debug-collector/+/52299/2..7//COMMIT_MSG#b7  with my concerns. Now bringing the same concern after merging original code , you should follow the guide lines on deprecating the features from existing code. Initiate the discussion in mailing list on the plan, and if community is ok or no response with in 2 weeks, initiate review to deprecate the plugins. 
Since this is not performance or memory critical am not seeing any harm in keeping the behavior same way.

It isn't the same concern. The items added in the new network plugin(52299) are required and distinct. What is being pointed out as redundant is the code that was already merged in master (iplink & ipaddr). 

I can initiate the discussion in mailing list /& start a thread on discord for the same.
On second look, this data is duplicate. We only need to capture ip addr which covers the link information too
+1 i have already pointed same in earlier review. Lot of data seem tyo be duplicate here.
Done
Looks right to me
data captured looks good to me
